<FeaturePage
  tagline="FEATURE // MULTI_AGENT"
  title="AI Agent Coordination"
  description="Run multiple AI agents on the same codebase. The OS resolves file conflicts at write time — no locks, no message buses, no coordination code."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>
  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>
    You spawn two agents. One refactors the auth module. The other adds a new API endpoint that imports from auth. Both edit <code>src/auth/middleware.js</code> within seconds.
  </p>
  <p>
    Without coordination, the last write wins and the first agent's work disappears. With locking, the second agent blocks for 40 turns of idle time. With message buses, both agents need a coordination protocol they were never trained on.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>
    The daemon (<code>ostk listen</code>) is the <a href="/docs/session-topology">anchor</a>. Agents run as managed sessions with heartbeat monitoring, <a href="/docs/session-topology">drain snapshots</a>, and crash recovery. The operator spawns workers directly:
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>ostk kernel spawn auth-refactor --model sonnet --budget 2 "Refactor auth to JWT"</code>
  </p>
  <p>
    Each agent works independently. When edits don't overlap, writes go through immediately. When they do, the kernel resolves the conflict.
  </p>

  <h2>Conflict resolution tiers</h2>
  <p>
    Every <code>file:edit()</code> is a compare-and-swap: the agent sends the <code>old_str</code> it expects to find and the <code>new_str</code> to replace it with. If <code>old_str</code> no longer matches — another agent modified it — the resolution tiers engage. No LLM is called. This is mechanical text diffing, implemented in <code>src/kernel/hotpr.rs</code>. Every conflict is recorded in the <a href="/features/audit-trail">audit trail</a>.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tier 1 — Auto-merge.</strong> The agent's intended edit and the other agent's changes are more than <code>PROXIMITY_LINES = 3</code> lines apart. Both changes apply silently. Neither agent is interrupted.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 2 — Assisted merge.</strong> Edits are within 3 lines of each other and under <code>TIER2_MAX_CHANGED_LINES = 30</code> changed lines, with at most <code>TIER2_MAX_CONFLICT_REGIONS = 2</code> conflict regions. The kernel computes a mechanical line rebase and returns a suggested <code>file:edit()</code> call the agent can accept, modify, or reject. Still no model call.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 3 — Manual rebase.</strong> Above Tier 2 thresholds. The kernel returns conflict info and the agent re-reads the file from disk. If the rebase falls through Tier 2 (tier2_line_rebase returns None), an ArbitrationObservation is written to <code>.ostk/audit.jsonl</code> — the Phase 0 observer for a future small-model arbiter.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fleet economics</h2>
  <p>
    The prompt cache at Anthropic's edge is content-addressed and per-organization. Two ostk processes with the same API key share cache entries automatically. Adding more agents amortizes the cold-write cost across readers. Fleet cost scales sublinearly.
  </p>
</FeaturePage>
